Devloping and analyzing robust and efficient finite element methods (FEMs) for solving electromagnetic wave propagation problems in complex media plays very important role in many areas of science and engineering, such as material sciences, physics, optics, and bioengineering.





During this project, the PI and his collaborators made some significant progress in devloping and analyzing for solving the time-dependent Maxwell's equations in complex media. More specifically, in the past 4 years, the PI has carried out systematic analysis and simulations of several popular perfectly matched layer (PML) models, such asZiolkowskis PML model {results published in 2022 "Journal of Computational Physics", and in 2023 "SIAM Journal on Numerical Analysis");an equivalent Berengers PML model (published in 2023 "ESAIM: Mathematical Modeling and Numerical Analysis");the Drude metamaterial PML model (published in 2024 "Journal of Computational and Applied Mathematics"). All these works are original, few lmathematical analysis has been done for these PML models.


In the past 4 years, we also carried out many innovative studies on electromagnetic wave propagation problems, such as


1. developed and studiedelectromagnetic rotation cloak model (published in 2024 "Journal of Scientific Computing");


2. hyperbolic metamaterials withapplications for hyperlens (published in 2024 "SIAM Journal on Numerical Analysis");


3. electromagnetic concentrator model (published in 2024 "Numerical Methods for Partial Differential Equations");


4. time-domain graphene model with simulations of propagation of surface plasmon polaritons (published in 2023 "Computers & Mathematics with Applications");


5. photonic crystalwaveguides comprising third-order nonlinear and linear materials (published in 2023 "Journal of Computational and Applied Mathematics");


6.Superconvergence analysis of finite element approximations to Maxwells equationsin both metamaterials and perfectly matched layers (published in 2024 "Computer & Mathematics with Applications").


In summary, our developed algorithms and anlysis of Maxwell's equations in metamaterials and grapene provide scientists and mathemticians better understanding of wave propagation in complex media and their potential applications inelectrical engineering, material sciences, optics, physics, nano-technology, and biomedical technology. The support of this project also gave the PI an opportunity to train some young computational mathematicians: The PI graduated one female PhD student in May 2023, and has attracted another US citizen to work with him in 2024,





